  "response": "**Finding to fix first: `crime_00004` (Half-UTC, Half-Local) in `src/date.ts`**\n\n**Receiver whose methods disagree:** `d`\n\nThe same `d: Date` is read with `getUTCFullYear()` at L9 (UTC family) and `getMonth()` at L41 (local family). The two values describe different moments whenever the host's UTC offset isn't zero — and L41 is also where `crime_00026` flags the hand-rolled string concatenation, so the formatting at L41 is the obvious blast site for the bug.\n\n**Refactor — pick UTC, end-to-end:**\n\n1. **Unify the family on `d` to UTC.** Replace `d.getMonth()` at L41 with `d.getUTCMonth()` (and any sibling reads in the same function — `getDate`/`getHours`/etc. → `getUTCDate`/`getUTCHours`). Rule of thumb: UTC for storage and computation, local only at the display boundary.\n2. **Drop the string-sewing while you're there.** Since the entire format string at L41 is now UTC, swap `\"…\" + d.getUTCFullYear() + …` for `d.toISOString().slice(0, 10)` (or `Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-CA', { timeZone: 'UTC', … }).format(d)` if you need a non-ISO shape). That collapses crime_00004 + crime_00026 into one change and removes the zero-padding / zero-indexed-month foot-guns.\n3. **Lock it with a test** that constructs `d` in a non-UTC zone (e.g. `TZ=America/Los_Angeles`) and asserts the formatted output — the current code would have failed this on Dec 31 evening Pacific time, where `getUTCFullYear()` returns 2027 but `getMonth()` returns 11 of 2026.\n\nLeave the other `src/date.ts` findings (`crime_00003` clock injection, `crime_00010` unsafe parses, `crime_00014` DST-naive `+ 86400000`, `crime_00027` locale drift) for follow-up commits — they're independent and would each muddy this diff.",
